window.CS_SPEC=window.CS_SPEC||{};window.CS_SPEC["TASK-IMP-121"]="<h1>TASK-IMP-121: Uninstall must leave the repo as it found it</h1>\n<h2>Summary</h2>\n<p>Uninstall deletes the machine and leaves things pointing at it. A byte-level harness on a fresh git repo found five dangling skill symlinks and two MCP registrations naming a server that is gone. Two further defects are byte-level: stripping our managed block from an operator's pre-commit hook leaves one newline behind every cycle, and doing the same to a pre-existing <code>.gitignore</code> leaves one behind once. A fifth defect runs the other way and the harness could not see it: <code>:118-119</code> <code>rmdir</code>s <code>.agents/skills</code> and <code>.agents</code> for emptiness alone, with no ownership test, so an operator's pre-existing empty <code>.agents/skills</code> is DESTROYED - reproduced end to end this round, and <code>.agents</code> with it when <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS</code> filters the antigravity pointer off. The harness's zero-casualty census holds only over its six cases as run, none of which had a pre-existing <code>.agents/skills</code>; it is not the general claim its wording invites. So the repo is left broken rather than merely untidy, two files an operator owns do not come back byte-identical, and one directory an operator owns does not come back at all.</p>\n<h2>Problem</h2>\n<p>Measured 2026-07-18. <code>uninstall.sh:151</code> runs <code>rm -rf \"$CY\"</code>; <code>:155-158</code> then recreates <code>.cyberos/memory/</code> and moves the stashed BRAIN back. <strong><code>.cyberos/</code> survives by default</strong> - what is gone in both modes is <code>plugin/</code>, <code>mcp/</code>, <code>cuo/</code>, <code>lib/</code>, <code>docs-tools/</code> and the root scripts. Every pointer install writes targets <code>.cyberos/plugin/skills/...</code> or <code>.cyberos/mcp/cyberos-mcp.mjs</code>, and both live in the part that is removed under <code>CYBEROS_UNINSTALL_KEEP_BRAIN=1</code> and <code>=0</code> alike. So the question is never \"does <code>.cyberos/</code> still exist\" - it is \"does this pointer name a path we deleted\", and that is answered by the pointer's own text.</p>\n<p><strong>1. Five dangling skill symlinks.</strong> Install writes six channels: <code>.agents/skills/</code>, <code>.claude/skills/</code>, <code>.grok/skills/</code>, <code>.commandcode/skills/</code>, <code>.codex/skills/</code>, <code>.opencode/skill/</code> (<code>:623-627</code>, <code>:631-632</code>, <code>:650-679</code>; note OpenCode's singular <code>skill</code>). Uninstall's loop (<code>:94</code>) looks at two. <code>.agents/skills/ship-tasks</code> is removed by <code>:98-99</code>; <code>.claude/skills/{task-author,task-audit}</code> by <code>:113-114</code>. <code>.claude/skills/ship-tasks</code> is exempted by name at <code>:112</code> (<code>[ \"$_sc\" != \"ship-tasks\" ]</code>), and <code>.grok</code>, <code>.commandcode</code>, <code>.codex</code>, <code>.opencode</code> are never looked at - <code>grep -ci</code> returns <strong>0</strong> for each of them in <code>uninstall.sh</code>. Five survivors, all <code>-&gt; ../../.cyberos/plugin/skills/ship-tasks</code>, all confirmed dangling.</p>\n<p><strong>2. Two dead MCP registrations.</strong> <code>.mcp.json</code> and <code>.cursor/mcp.json</code> both register <code>node .cyberos/mcp/cyberos-mcp.mjs</code> (<code>:685-688</code>). Uninstall never unregisters - <code>grep -ci mcp</code> returns 0. Every agent reading those configs launches a missing server on every startup, in a repo the operator just cleaned.</p>\n<p><strong>3. The hook gains a newline every cycle.</strong> Install appends its block with <code>cat &gt;&gt; \"$hk\" &lt;&lt;'HOOK'</code> whose heredoc's <strong>first line is blank</strong> (<code>:851-853</code>), so the file gains <code>\\n# &gt;&gt;&gt; cyberos-status-hook v2</code>. <code>uninstall.sh:68</code>'s sed range starts <strong>at</strong> the marker, so the blank above it survives. Proven by the harness at 29 -&gt; 30 -&gt; 31 -&gt; 32 bytes over three cycles, final tail <code>exit 0\\n\\n\\n\\n</code>; reproduced this round at 7 -&gt; 8 -&gt; 9 -&gt; 10 on a 7-byte fixture. Unbounded: nothing ever trims it.</p>\n<p><strong>4. The same defect in <code>.gitignore</code>, which the first draft missed.</strong> <code>install.sh:747</code> writes <code>[ -s \"$gi.cyberos.tmp\" ] &amp;&amp; printf '\\n'</code> before the block, and <code>uninstall.sh:80</code>'s sed range also starts at the marker. Measured by replaying both verbatim: a pre-existing <code>.gitignore</code> goes <strong>14 -&gt; 15 bytes</strong> and stays at 15 across three cycles - <code>install.sh:745</code>'s awk trims the trailing blank run on re-install, so this leak is one-time rather than accumulating. It is still a mutation of an operator's file, and it is why the fix belongs to the strip, not to the hook.</p>\n<p>The <code>[ -s ]</code> guard at <code>:747</code> also explains the separate <code>.gitignore</code> symptom the harness saw: where install <strong>created</strong> the file (<code>:706</code>), the tmp is empty, no separator is written, and the strip leaves a 0-byte file.</p>\n<p><strong>5. A directory an operator owns is destroyed - the one defect that runs the other way.</strong> <code>uninstall.sh:118-119</code> <code>rmdir</code>s <code>.agents/skills</code> and then <code>.agents</code>, each <code>2&gt;/dev/null || true</code>. Neither carries an ownership test: <code>rmdir</code>'s refusal on a non-empty directory is the ONLY guard, and it does not fire when the directory is an operator's and happens to be empty. Reproduced end to end this round: a fresh git repo with an operator's pre-existing empty <code>.agents/skills</code>, install, then uninstall - <code>.agents/skills</code> is GONE. In the default config <code>.agents</code> survives, but only incidentally: the <code>:588</code> antigravity pointer writes <code>.agents/rules/cyberos.md</code>, no uninstall code path removes it (<code>grep -n 'rules/' uninstall.sh</code> returns only <code>:92</code>, a comment, and that comment names <code>.devin/rules/</code>, <code>.windsurf/rules/</code> and <code>.windsurfrules</code> - not <code>.agents/rules/</code>), and the directory is therefore never empty. Filter antigravity off (<code>CYBEROS_AGENTS=agents</code>) and <code>find .agents</code> after uninstall returns nothing - the operator's <code>.agents</code> goes too. This is a §1.9 casualty, and it is the reason the container rule below is a marker gate rather than a blanket refusal to prune.</p>\n<p><strong>Against section 6.</strong> <code>uninstall.sh:162</code> reads <code># 6. skill symlinks into .cyberos (dangling) - leave dirs; operator cleans</code>. The dangling is <strong>known and deliberate</strong>, and <code>:111</code>'s comment records the same posture for <code>.claude/skills/ship-tasks</code>. This is a decision to overturn, not a gap to fill. It is overturned because its premise does not survive contact with <code>:113-114</code>. The restraint section 6 encodes is the right instinct about <em>operator files</em> - and a symlink whose target text names our own machine is not an operator file. <code>:113-114</code> already trusts exactly that proof to remove <code>task-author</code> and <code>task-audit</code>, in the same run that leaves <code>ship-tasks</code> dangling. Section 6 is not restraint applied consistently; it is one channel's entry escaping a test its two siblings pass. Leaving a pointer to a file we deleted protects nobody.</p>\n<p><strong>What ownership can and cannot be proven from - and what install can be made to record.</strong> The discipline <code>:98-99</code> and <code>:113-114</code> use is: read the artefact, decide from what it says. It generalises to every artefact here - a marker-delimited block, an MCP command naming our path, a <code>.cyberos-owned</code> file. Where it stops is the <em>container</em>, and it stops there for a contingent reason rather than a necessary one. Whether install <em>created</em> <code>.gitignore</code> or <code>.mcp.json</code> is recorded nowhere: <code>install.sh</code>'s <code>wrote</code>, <code>AGENT_FILES</code> and <code>SKILL_DIRS</code> (<code>:479</code>, <code>:580</code>, <code>:621</code>, <code>:686</code>) are shell variables that die with the process, and an operator who ran <code>touch .gitignore</code> before install is byte-indistinguishable from install's <code>: &gt; \"$gi\"</code> (<code>:706</code>). No clause below conditions on that.</p>\n<p>But the container question is not undecidable in general - it is unrecorded, and install is the thing that would record it. <strong>It already does, one directory too low.</strong> <code>:672-675</code> writes a <code>.cyberos-owned</code> marker into each <code>.agents/skills/&lt;cmd&gt;</code> copy dir, <code>:101</code> reads it, and <code>:137</code> states the principle the marker exists to serve: <em>\"what we did not create, we do not silently destroy.\"</em> Measured: <code>.agents/skills/.cyberos-owned</code> is ABSENT while <code>.agents/skills</code> EXISTS, because <code>:675</code> redirects into <code>$_sdest</code> - the skill dir (<code>:653</code>), not its parent. The parent carries no proof, which is exactly why <code>:118</code>'s <code>rmdir</code> is blind and deletes an operator's pre-existing empty <code>.agents/skills</code>. §1.11 moves that same marker up one level, under a create-test; §1.6 gates the <code>rmdir</code> on it. This is TASK-IMP-094's mechanism applied to the dir above, not a new one.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the marker set is two dirs and not six.</strong> <code>grep -n 'rmdir' uninstall.sh</code> returns <code>:118</code> (<code>.agents/skills</code>), <code>:119</code> (<code>.agents</code>) and <code>:158</code> (the BRAIN stash tmpdir). Those are the only directories uninstall can remove, so they are the only ones a marker changes a decision about. The five native channel parents are never <code>rmdir</code>'d - <code>grep -ci</code> returns 0 for grok/commandcode/codex/opencode/cursor - so marking them would write a file nothing reads and, because those dirs are never removed, would leave every one of those markers behind as a new permanent leftover. That is the defect this task exists to remove, arriving through the fix for it. The rule is therefore: mark exactly what the prune can delete.</p>\n<p><strong>Two proofs, not one, and they do not generalise alike.</strong> The direct form (<code>:613</code>) writes a target naming <code>.cyberos/plugin/skills/&lt;entry&gt;</code>: that text names the machine we deleted, so it proves ownership for <em>any</em> entry under <em>any</em> channel. The chained form (<code>:662</code>) writes <code>.agents/skills/&lt;cmd&gt; -&gt; ../../.claude/skills/&lt;cmd&gt;</code>, which names no <code>.cyberos/</code> path at all - it is ours only <em>by construction</em>, and only for the three names <code>:649</code>'s <code>SHARED_CMDS</code> lists. Generalising the chained pattern to every entry in the directory would keep the pattern and destroy the justification: an operator's <code>.agents/skills/my-notes -&gt; ../../.claude/skills/my-notes</code> matches it exactly and is not ours. The two forms are therefore separated below, and only the direct one is name-blind.</p>\n<h2>Proposed Solution</h2>\n<p>Extend the readlink ownership test to every channel install writes, and apply the same read-the-artefact discipline to the MCP registrations and to both managed blocks. Four proofs, each evaluated at uninstall time from the artefact itself:</p>\n<table><thead><tr><th>artefact</th><th>proof it is ours</th><th>generalises?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>skill symlink, direct form</td><td><code>readlink</code> target text naming <code>.cyberos/plugin/skills/&lt;entry&gt;</code> (<code>:98</code>)</td><td>yes - the text names our deleted machine</td></tr><tr><td>skill symlink, chained form</td><td>ours by construction (<code>install.sh:662</code>)</td><td>no - only the three <code>:649</code> names, only under <code>.agents/skills/</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>.agents/skills</code> copy dir</td><td>the <code>.cyberos-owned</code> file it carries (<code>:101</code>)</td><td>yes - the marker is ours</td></tr><tr><td><code>.agents/skills</code> and <code>.agents</code> themselves</td><td>the <code>.cyberos-owned</code> marker §1.11 has install write when, and only when, install CREATES the dir</td><td>no - only these two dirs, because only these two can be <code>rmdir</code>'d (<code>:118-119</code>)</td></tr><tr><td><code>.gitignore</code> / hook block</td><td>the <code># &gt;&gt;&gt;</code> / <code># &lt;&lt;&lt;</code> marker pair delimiting it</td><td>yes - the markers are ours</td></tr><tr><td>MCP registration</td><td>the command naming <code>.cyberos/mcp/cyberos-mcp.mjs</code></td><td>yes - the command names our deleted machine</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><strong>The predicate is textual, never resolution.</strong> <code>readlink</code> returns a string; a target naming our machine proves ownership whether or not it still resolves. This is what makes the rule identical under <code>CYBEROS_UNINSTALL_KEEP_BRAIN=1</code> (where <code>.cyberos/</code> survives with BRAIN inside) and <code>=0</code> (where it does not), and it is why an operator's own broken symlink pointing elsewhere is untouched: unresolvable is not the same as unowned, in either direction.</p>\n<p><strong>What is provably ours is removed; a container is removed only when its creation is proven too.</strong> The block comes out of <code>.gitignore</code>, the file stays. The registration comes out of <code>.mcp.json</code>, the file stays with an empty registry. The symlink goes, the channel dir stays. For <code>.gitignore</code>, <code>.mcp.json</code> and the five native channel parents the line is drawn where the proof runs out, and nothing below moves it: an emptied container is inert, and unprovable ownership is not a licence to delete.</p>\n<p><code>.agents/skills</code> and <code>.agents</code> are the two exceptions, because they are the only containers uninstall can remove (<code>:118-119</code>) and therefore the only ones where the proof is worth recording. <strong>Install records it.</strong> §1.11 has install write <code>.cyberos-owned</code> into each of those two dirs when, and only when, install itself creates the dir; §1.6 then permits the <code>rmdir</code> only for a dir carrying that marker and only once it is empty. Where install created the dir, uninstall takes it back and leaves nothing behind. Where the operator's dir predated install, there is no marker, the dir is kept, and uninstall says so - which is what <code>:118</code> fails to do today.</p>\n<p><strong>The trap this must not walk into, and the test that avoids it.</strong> <code>mkdir -p</code> succeeds silently on a directory that already exists (measured: exit 0). So <code>mkdir -p \"$d\"</code> followed by an unconditional marker write would stamp an operator's pre-existing directory as ours - the current bug inverted, and strictly worse, because today's defect merely deletes an unproven dir while that one would manufacture the proof first. The create-test must therefore run BEFORE the <code>mkdir</code>, in the shape <code>[ -d \"$d\" ] || { mkdir -p \"$d\"; marker \"$d\"; }</code>. Two measured facts stop that shape from being applied once and reused: <code>mkdir -p a/b</code> creates <strong>both</strong> levels, so a marker in <code>.agents/skills</code> says nothing about <code>.agents</code>; and <code>.agents</code> has a <strong>second creator</strong> at <code>:566</code> (the <code>:588</code> antigravity pointer, whose dirname is <code>.agents/rules</code>) which runs before <code>:660</code>. <code>.agents</code> therefore needs its own test, evaluated before the first line that can create it. §1.11 states both.</p>\n<p><strong>Ownership and capability are different questions, and <code>.mcp.json</code> needs both.</strong> What proves the <em>registration</em> is ours is its command text, exactly as <code>readlink</code> output proves a symlink. What byte-identity to <code>install.sh:685</code>'s form decides is something else entirely: whether <code>uninstall.sh</code> can rewrite the file <strong>without a JSON parser it does not have</strong>. So byte-identity is a capability gate, not an ownership test - which is why the prior draft's own objection (\"byte-identity proves the content is ours; it cannot prove the file is\") is correct and does not bite: nothing below uses byte-identity to prove the file is ours, and the file is never deleted either way.</p>\n<p><strong>Strip the separator with the block, by bytes and not by lines.</strong> Install always appends exactly one <code>\\n</code> immediately before the <code># &gt;&gt;&gt;</code> marker (<code>:851-853</code>, <code>:913-915</code>: the heredoc's first line is blank), so the byte immediately before the marker is always ours. The strip must delete <strong>that byte</strong>, not that line. Measured: the line-oriented rule restores a newline-terminated hook exactly but adds a byte to a hook with no trailing newline (6B -&gt; 7B); the byte-oriented rule is byte-exact for both, and for a hook ending in three newlines, and for a hook with content above and no trailing newline.</p>\n<h2>Alternatives Considered</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Have install write a RECEIPT - a manifest of what it created - so uninstall can know rather than guess.</strong> Rejected in favour of the marker, which is what §1.11 adopts; the underlying instinct (<em>install should record what it made</em>) is correct and is what option C implements. Adopted in a different form for TASK-IMP-122, where the underivable fact (what <code>install.sh</code> vendors) is load-bearing and has no safe fallback. Here the marker beats the receipt on every axis that matters: it is <strong>local to the artefact</strong> where a receipt is a new cross-script contract with a format and staleness semantics across re-installs; it needs no parser; it survives an operator moving the repo; and install <strong>already writes one</strong> at <code>:672-675</code>, so §1.11 moves an existing mechanism up a level rather than introducing one. Both share the one real hazard - a record that wrongly claims creation would delete an operator's directory, the single outcome §1.9 forbids - and §1.11 closes it the only way either could: by testing existence BEFORE <code>mkdir</code>, never after. Note what neither rescues: nothing about removing one key from JSON an operator has since edited (§1.5), and nothing about <code>.gitignore</code>'s pre-install shape (§3), which install destroys before uninstall ever runs. The prior draft rejected the marker partly because it was an <code>install.sh</code> change and <code>install.sh</code> was out of scope; the operator's decision puts it in scope, so that half of the argument is retired rather than carried forward.</li><li><strong>Option A: never delete the parent - keep all six channel dirs and remove <code>:118-119</code> outright.</strong> The prior author's §1.6, and the operator's decision <strong>overturns it</strong>. It is safe and it is honest, and its cost is that where install CREATED <code>.agents/skills</code>, uninstall now leaves an empty directory behind in a repo it promised to leave as it found it - trading a false positive for a permanent one. It was only ever forced by the belief that creation is unknowable; measurement says it is merely unrecorded, and <code>:672-675</code> shows install already recording it one level down. Rejected on that basis, not on taste.</li><li><strong>Option B: leave the bug and scope the container clause to the other five dirs.</strong> Rejected by the operator, and it fails on its own terms regardless: §1.9 forbids deleting a path present before install whatever §1.6 says, so scoping §1.6 around <code>:118</code> would leave the casualty in place and merely stop naming it. Audit 2 raised exactly this as NEW-002 (an AC that cannot be satisfied while <code>:118</code> stands); re-scoping the clause answers the auditor and not the operator whose directory is gone.</li><li><strong>Delete an emptied container when it is byte-identical to install's exact output.</strong> Rejected: that is the TASK-IMP-118 defect in miniature. Install's <code>.mcp.json</code> is a fixed 5-line, 105-byte string (measured) and <code>install.sh:689</code>'s own summary points operators at <code>.cyberos/mcp/README.md</code> to hand-register (<code>:683</code>'s comment says the same), so an operator-authored file can be byte-identical to ours. Byte-identity proves the <em>content</em> is ours; it cannot prove the <em>file</em> is. §1.4 uses it only as a capability gate, never as a licence to delete.</li><li><strong>Trim trailing blank lines after the strip instead of consuming the separator.</strong> Rejected: an operator hook whose pre-install content legitimately ends in three newlines would come back with one. Measured - the correct rule removes exactly one <em>byte</em> immediately above the marker, and that is byte-exact for the three-newline shape (9B -&gt; 9B) as well as the no-newline shape (6B -&gt; 6B).</li><li><strong>Keep the prior draft's line-oriented strip and record the no-trailing-newline hook as impossible.</strong> Rejected because the impossibility is false, and measurement says so: the byte-oriented rule inverts that shape (6B -&gt; 6B). The error was a level confusion - the rule was reasoned about in line-space, where the no-newline case has no blank line to consume, and \"my line rule cannot\" was generalised to \"no rule can\". Install's <code>cat &gt;&gt;</code> is injective on hook content, so an inverse must exist; only the line-oriented expression of it fails.</li><li><strong>Mark all six channel parents rather than the two the prune can reach.</strong> Rejected on measurement, and named because \"apply the marker to the channel's parent skills dir\" reads naturally as <em>all</em> of them. <code>grep -n 'rmdir' uninstall.sh</code> returns only <code>:118</code>, <code>:119</code> and <code>:158</code> (the BRAIN tmpdir): the five native channel parents are never removed, so a marker under them changes no decision - nothing reads it - and, because those dirs survive, each marker would itself survive as a new permanent leftover in a repo this task promises to leave as it found it. The fix would ship the defect. Mark exactly what the prune can delete.</li><li><strong>Remove the whole agent surface on uninstall.</strong> Rejected: <code>.cursorrules</code>, <code>GEMINI.md</code> and the rules pointers may predate install or carry operator edits; unprovable ownership is not a licence to delete. TASK-IMP-094's recorded reasoning, and it still holds.</li><li><strong>Leave the dangling links and let TASK-IMP-106's summary name them.</strong> Rejected: 106 §1.5 forbids changing behaviour, so it can only describe the breakage honestly. A truthful report of a broken repo is not a fixed repo.</li><li><strong>Effort 9 -&gt; 12 hours.</strong> The prior 9h assumed <code>install.sh</code> was untouched; option C makes the create-detection and both parent markers install-side, and <code>modified_files</code> now says so. Breakdown: channel loop rewrite (direct form, all six, name-blind) 1h; chained/direct split 0.5h; MCP partition 1.5h; byte-exact strip 1.5h; <strong>install-side create-detection + the two parent markers (two dirs, two creation sites, pre-<code>mkdir</code> tests) 1.5h</strong>; <strong>uninstall-side marker-gated prune + marker-removal sequencing 1h</strong>; <code>t22</code> rename + re-point 0.5h; suite 4.5h. Sum: 1 + 0.5 + 1.5 + 1.5 + 1.5 + 1 + 0.5 + 4.5 = <strong>12</strong>. The suite line carries +1 over the prior 3.5h for the three new arms AC 11/AC 12 need (created -&gt; pruned, pre-existing -&gt; kept, adopted -&gt; kept), each requiring a distinct <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS</code> fixture.</li></ul>\n<h2>Success Metrics</h2>\n<ul><li>Primary: zero surviving pointers naming a path under <code>.cyberos/</code>, asserted by reading every surviving symlink target and every MCP command after uninstall. Baseline: 5 dangling symlinks + 2 dead registrations, measured 2026-07-18.</li><li>Primary: an operator's pre-existing hook and <code>.gitignore</code> are byte-identical to their pre-install bytes after 1 and after 3 cycles, asserted with <code>cmp</code>, over the shapes §1.7 binds on. Baseline: hook +1 per cycle (7 -&gt; 8 -&gt; 9 -&gt; 10 on a 7-byte fixture; 29 -&gt; 30 -&gt; 31 -&gt; 32 in the harness); <code>.gitignore</code> +1 once (14 -&gt; 15).</li><li>Guardrail: zero casualties - no path present before install is missing, and none is mutated except by the removal of content proven ours (§1.9). Baseline: 0 across the harness's six cases; it must stay 0, and the leak fixes must not create one.</li><li>Guardrail: every container that existed BEFORE install still exists after uninstall - including an operator's pre-existing empty <code>.agents/skills</code> and <code>.agents</code> - and every container install CREATED and marked is either removed with its marker or kept and reported. Baseline measured 2026-07-18: an operator's pre-existing empty <code>.agents/skills</code> is DELETED by <code>:118</code> (reproduced end to end), and with <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS=agents</code> their <code>.agents</code> is deleted by <code>:119</code> as well. This metric exists to keep the fix from over-reaching in the other direction - a create-detection that marks a pre-existing dir would satisfy the removal half while manufacturing the casualty.</li><li>Guardrail: no <code>.cyberos-owned</code> file exists anywhere under the repo after uninstall. Baseline: not applicable today (install writes markers only into skill copy dirs, which uninstall removes wholesale at <code>:102</code>); it becomes load-bearing the moment §1.11 writes markers into two dirs that uninstall may KEEP, and it is what stops the fix from leaving litter of its own.</li></ul>\n<h2>Scope</h2>\n<p>In scope: <code>uninstall.sh</code>'s handling of the six skill channels, the two MCP registrations, the separator on both managed-block strips, and <code>:118-119</code>'s <code>rmdir</code>, now gated on the marker rather than removed; <code>install.sh</code>'s create-detection and the two parent markers it writes (<code>:566</code>/<code>:588</code> and <code>:660</code>); the suite arms for each; the rename and re-point of TASK-IMP-106's <code>t22</code>.</p>\n<h3>Out of scope / Non-Goals</h3>\n<ul><li><strong>Everything on the install side except the two parent markers and their create-tests.</strong> The prior draft excluded <code>install.sh</code> entirely; the operator's option-C decision makes that impossible, so the exclusion is narrowed rather than kept. Specifically still out: <code>.gitignore</code>'s pre-install shape, destroyed by <code>:733-746</code>'s awk before uninstall runs (§3 - a true pigeonhole, re-measured this round); and the <code>CYBEROS_COPY_SKILLS=1</code> copy under the five native channels, which carries no marker (§3). The second is now out on its own merits rather than on \"install.sh is out of scope\": it is an ENTRY-level ownership question under dirs the prune cannot reach, where §1.6's container rule does not apply and §1.3 already keeps and reports the entry. Marking those copies would widen the task without changing any deletion this spec authorises.</li><li>What uninstall KEEPS by design (<code>docs/tasks/</code>, <code>docs/status/</code>, <code>CHANGELOG.md</code>, <code>AGENTS.md</code>/pointer files, BRAIN). Correct, and untouched.</li><li>The rules pointers (<code>.cursorrules</code>, <code>.windsurfrules</code>, <code>GEMINI.md</code>, <code>.github/copilot-instructions.md</code>, <code>.agents/rules/</code>, <code>.devin/rules/</code>, <code>.cursor/rules/</code>). Agent surface, kept for the same reason as <code>CLAUDE.md</code>. (<code>uninstall.sh:92-93</code>'s comment records only three of these; the rest are covered by the same reasoning, not by that citation.)</li><li>Payload staleness detection - TASK-IMP-122.</li><li>The summary's wording - TASK-IMP-106 owns it.</li></ul>\n<h2>Dependencies</h2>\n<p>depends_on TASK-IMP-106: both edit <code>uninstall.sh</code> and <code>test_install_hygiene.sh</code>, so they serialise. 106 lands first, creating <code>t22_uninstall_behavior_unchanged</code>, whose AC 3 pins \"the set of files present after uninstall is byte-identical to today's behavior\" - a test that freezes every defect above as correct. This task MUST re-point and rename it (§1.10); shipping 121 without doing so turns 106's green suite red. 106 §1.5 keeps its verification: the re-pointed test still fails any summary change that alters what uninstall removes or keeps, which is the whole of what §1.5 asks. Per TASK-IMP-101's evidence gate, 106's coverage-gate artefact is the evidence.</p>\n<h2>AI Authorship Disclosure</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Tools used:</strong> Claude (Opus 4.8) running the CyberOS task-author skill inside Cowork.</li><li><strong>Scope:</strong> §1.6 re-done and §1.11/§1.12 added 2026-07-18 by a FOURTH author to implement the operator's option-C decision, which overturns the third author's §1.6. The rest of the document was inherited from the third author's rewrite and re-read in full rather than patched where named - the standing failure mode across eight audits and four authors is that authors do not check what they ORIGINATE, and round 3's defect was patching only what the audit pointed at. What this author re-verified against source and by measurement, with the derivations in <code>source_pages</code>: the marker write (<code>:672-675</code>) and its read (<code>:101</code>); the <code>:118-119</code> rmdir; the bug itself, reproduced end to end; <code>:119</code>'s reachability under <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS=agents</code>; both <code>mkdir -p</code> traps; the two creators of <code>.agents</code>; the <code>.gitignore</code> pigeonhole (reproduces exactly); and the byte-oriented strip (all four shapes exact). <strong>One inherited claim did not survive and is corrected rather than carried:</strong> the third author's own recorded limit (\"want 17B, got 18B\") reproduces, but its CAUSE is awk's <code>print</code> appending ORS, not the byte-oriented rule - <code>printf \"%s\"</code> is byte-exact on the same shape. <strong>One claim this author originated is flagged as unverified rather than asserted:</strong> the byte-oriented strip was measured only on GNU Awk 5.1.0, and its <code>RS=\"^$\"</code> slurp is a GNU extension while the payload's floor is POSIX (<code>install.sh:98</code>) and runs on macOS's BSD awk. §1.7 binds on behaviour, not on awk, so the clause survives - but the gawk form must not be assumed to port. <strong>And one defect this author originated was caught by re-reading its own citations rather than by an auditor:</strong> three passages cited <code>uninstall.sh:92-93</code> as the reason <code>.agents/rules/cyberos.md</code> survives - which is audit 1's ISS-006 exactly, a comment naming three paths stretched to cover a fourth it does not name. It survives because no uninstall code path removes it (<code>grep -n 'rules/' uninstall.sh</code> returns only <code>:92</code>); all three now say so. Recorded rather than quietly fixed, because the pattern this round exists to break is that originated claims are never checked, and the shortest distance to repeating it is to fix your own slip silently.</li><li><strong>Human review:</strong> scope and the <code>:112</code> refinement approved at the 2026-07-18 PLAN gate; both HITL gates are recorded human verdicts. <strong>The <code>:118-119</code> scope question the third author flagged as needing an operator verdict has been answered:</strong> the operator was offered A (never delete), B (leave the bug, scope the clause to five) and C (delete only if we can prove we made it) and <strong>chose C</strong> on 2026-07-18. That decision is recorded in <code>source_decisions</code>, closes audit.md §3.3, and is not relitigated here. It also disproves the infeasibility claim attached to C (\"nothing records who created the folder\") - install records it at <code>:672-675</code>, one directory too low, which is the whole of what §1.11 moves.</li></ul>\n<h2>1. Description (normative)</h2>\n<ul><li>1.1 After uninstall, no symlink under any channel install writes (<code>.agents/skills/</code>, <code>.claude/skills/</code>, <code>.grok/skills/</code>, <code>.commandcode/skills/</code>, <code>.codex/skills/</code>, <code>.opencode/skill/</code>) may remain whose <code>readlink</code> target text names <code>.cyberos/plugin/skills/&lt;entry&gt;</code>. Ownership MUST be decided from the target TEXT, never from whether the target resolves and never from the entry's name; no entry may be exempt by name, which removes <code>:112</code>'s <code>ship-tasks</code> guard.</li><li>1.2 The CHAINED form (<code>readlink</code> target naming <code>.claude/skills/&lt;entry&gt;</code>, which names no <code>.cyberos/</code> path and is ours only by construction) MUST be removed ONLY for the three names <code>install.sh:649</code> writes (<code>ship-tasks</code>, <code>task-author</code>, <code>task-audit</code>) and ONLY under <code>.agents/skills/</code>, because that is the exact set install creates it for (<code>:662</code>); it MUST NOT be generalised to other entries or other channels.</li><li>1.3 An entry under those channels whose ownership is proven by neither §1.1 nor §1.2 nor a <code>.cyberos-owned</code> marker it carries (<code>:101</code>) MUST be left byte-identical and reported as kept - including a real directory without our marker, a symlink whose target names neither form, and a BROKEN symlink whose target names neither form.</li><li>1.4 Where <code>.mcp.json</code> or <code>.cursor/mcp.json</code> carries a registration whose command names <code>.cyberos/mcp/cyberos-mcp.mjs</code> AND the file is byte-identical to the form <code>install.sh:685</code> generates, that registration MUST be removed, leaving the file present and carrying a registry with no entries. The command text proves the registration is ours; byte-identity is only the gate that lets <code>uninstall.sh</code> rewrite the file without a JSON parser.</li><li>1.5 Where <code>.mcp.json</code> or <code>.cursor/mcp.json</code> carries our registration but is NOT byte-identical to that form, the file has content install did not write; uninstall MUST NOT edit it, and MUST report the dead registration and the file's path so the operator can remove it by hand.</li><li>1.6 A container install writes into MUST survive uninstall when emptied of our content - <code>.gitignore</code> (including one install created at <code>:706</code>), <code>.mcp.json</code>, <code>.cursor/mcp.json</code>, and each of §1.1's six channel directories - EXCEPT that <code>.agents/skills</code> and <code>.agents</code> MUST be removed when, and only when, the directory carries the <code>.cyberos-owned</code> marker §1.11 writes AND is empty once our content and that marker are gone; emptiness alone MUST NOT authorise removing any container, so an unmarked <code>.agents/skills</code> or <code>.agents</code> MUST be kept and reported as kept, which is what <code>uninstall.sh:118-119</code>'s unconditional <code>rmdir</code> fails to do today.</li><li>1.7 Stripping a managed block MUST restore the file byte-identical to its pre-install content by deleting the block together with the single <code>\\n</code> byte install writes immediately before the <code># &gt;&gt;&gt;</code> marker (<code>install.sh:851-853</code>/<code>:913-915</code> for the hook, <code>:747</code> for <code>.gitignore</code>) - exactly one byte, never a line, and never a trailing-blank normalisation. For the pre-commit hook this binds on ALL pre-install content, including content with no trailing newline. For <code>.gitignore</code> it binds where the pre-install content is newline-terminated and does not end in a blank run; §3 records why the remaining <code>.gitignore</code> shapes are unrecoverable from <code>uninstall.sh</code> and which install-side line destroys them.</li><li>1.8 Uninstall MUST be idempotent over cycles: for any N &gt;= 1, N install/uninstall cycles MUST leave an operator's pre-existing hook and <code>.gitignore</code> byte-identical to their pre-install content, over the shapes §1.7 binds on.</li><li>1.9 No path present before install may be MISSING after uninstall, and none may be MUTATED except by the removal of content proven ours by its own text under §1.1-§1.5. The exception is on content only: no file and no directory present before install may be deleted, whatever its content proves.</li><li>1.10 The suite MUST NOT assert that the pre-121 leftovers are correct. TASK-IMP-106's <code>t22_uninstall_behavior_unchanged</code> MUST be re-pointed at the set §1.1-§1.7 define and renamed, because a test whose baseline has deliberately moved cannot honestly be named <code>_unchanged</code>.</li><li>1.11 <code>install.sh</code> MUST write a <code>.cyberos-owned</code> marker into <code>.agents/skills</code> and, separately, into <code>.agents</code> when and only when install itself CREATES that directory, deciding creation by testing that directory's own existence BEFORE any <code>mkdir -p</code> that could create it (<code>:660</code> for <code>.agents/skills</code>; <code>:566</code> reached via the <code>:588</code> antigravity pointer, which runs first, for <code>.agents</code>) - a directory that existed before install MUST NOT be marked, since <code>mkdir -p</code> succeeds silently on an existing directory and creates every level of the chain, so a post-<code>mkdir</code> test would prove install's own creation of an operator's directory; each marker's text MUST name the directory it marks and MUST carry the adoption sentence <code>:674-675</code> already gives the copy dirs.</li><li>1.12 Uninstall MUST remove a <code>.cyberos-owned</code> marker it finds on <code>.agents/skills</code> or on <code>.agents</code> before attempting that directory's <code>rmdir</code> and whether or not the <code>rmdir</code> then succeeds, so that no marker survives uninstall even where the directory is kept; and a directory whose marker the operator has deleted MUST be kept and reported as kept, honouring for the parent the adoption promise <code>install.sh:674-675</code> makes (\"Delete it to adopt the directory as your own; uninstall will then leave it alone\").</li></ul>\n<h2>2. Acceptance criteria</h2>\n<ul><li>[ ] AC 1 (traces_to: #1.1) - after an install writing all six channels, every surviving symlink under them is read with <code>readlink</code> and NONE has a target naming <code>.cyberos/plugin/skills/&lt;entry&gt;</code>; the test MUST assert all six channels separately and MUST FAIL if any entry is exempt by name, which today's <code>:112</code> guard makes true of <code>ship-tasks</code> - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t23_direct_target_links_removed_all_channels</code></li><li>[ ] AC 2 (traces_to: #1.2) - <code>.agents/skills/{ship-tasks,task-author,task-audit}</code> chained links are removed, AND an operator's <code>.agents/skills/my-notes -&gt; ../../.claude/skills/my-notes</code> survives byte-identical; the test MUST FAIL if the chained rule removes any name outside <code>install.sh:649</code>'s three or fires under any channel but <code>.agents/skills/</code> - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t24_chained_form_bounded_to_shared_cmds</code></li><li>[ ] AC 3 (traces_to: #1.3) - an operator's unmarked skill dir, an operator symlink whose target names neither form, AND an operator's BROKEN symlink whose target names neither form all survive byte-identical and are named as kept; the test MUST FAIL if an unresolvable target alone causes removal - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t25_unprovable_entries_kept_and_named</code></li><li>[ ] AC 4 (traces_to: #1.4) - where <code>.mcp.json</code> and <code>.cursor/mcp.json</code> are byte-identical to install's 105-byte form, after uninstall each file EXISTS, parses, carries zero registry entries, and contains no string naming <code>.cyberos/</code> - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t26_sole_cyberos_registration_removed</code></li><li>[ ] AC 5 (traces_to: #1.5) - an <code>.mcp.json</code> carrying our registration plus an operator's own is byte-identical after uninstall AND the dead registration is reported with the file's path; the test MUST FAIL if the file is edited at all - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t27_operator_edited_mcp_kept_and_named</code></li><li>[ ] AC 6 (traces_to: #1.6) - after install into a repo whose <code>.agents/skills</code> and <code>.agents</code> PRE-EXISTED, both still EXIST after uninstall and are reported as kept, alongside a <code>.gitignore</code> install created, an <code>.mcp.json</code> emptied of our registration and the five native channel dirs; and after install into a repo with neither, both are REMOVED; the test MUST FAIL if emptiness alone removes an unmarked dir, which today's <code>:118-119</code> makes true of both - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t28_containers_removed_only_when_proven_ours</code></li><li>[ ] AC 7 (traces_to: #1.7) - pre-existing hooks ending in no newline, one newline, and three newlines, plus a newline-terminated <code>.gitignore</code>, are each byte-identical to their pre-install bytes after one cycle, asserted with <code>cmp</code>; the test MUST FAIL on today's leak (hook 7 -&gt; 8, <code>.gitignore</code> 14 -&gt; 15) and on any rule that restores the no-newline hook to 7 bytes - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t29_block_strip_restores_byte_exact</code></li><li>[ ] AC 8 (traces_to: #1.8) - the hook (all three shapes) and the <code>.gitignore</code> are byte-identical to their pre-install bytes after each of 1, 2 and 3 cycles, witnessing the fixed point §1.8 asserts for all N; the test MUST compare bytes and not line counts, and MUST FAIL on today's 7 -&gt; 8 -&gt; 9 -&gt; 10 hook accumulation - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t30_strip_idempotent_over_cycles</code></li><li>[ ] AC 9 (traces_to: #1.9) - no path present before install is missing after uninstall, and none is mutated except by removal of content proven ours, across a fresh-git repo, a repo with a foreign hook, a repo with <code>core.hooksPath</code> set, a repo with a pre-existing EMPTY <code>.agents/skills</code>, a repo with a pre-existing hand-registered <code>.mcp.json</code>, and a repo uninstalled with <code>CYBEROS_UNINSTALL_KEEP_BRAIN=0</code> - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t31_no_casualties</code></li><li>[ ] AC 10 (traces_to: #1.10) - <code>t22</code> is renamed <code>t22_uninstall_removal_set_pinned</code>, pins the set §1.1-§1.7 define, and passes; the test MUST FAIL if any assertion in the suite still pins a pre-121 leftover as correct - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t22_uninstall_removal_set_pinned</code></li><li>[ ] AC 11 (traces_to: #1.11) - after install into a repo with a PRE-EXISTING <code>.agents</code> and <code>.agents/skills</code> NEITHER carries <code>.cyberos-owned</code>, and after install into a repo with neither directory BOTH carry it with text naming the directory and containing the adoption sentence; the test MUST FAIL if any pre-existing directory is marked, and MUST cover <code>.agents</code> being created alone via the <code>:588</code> pointer under <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS=antigravity</code> and <code>.agents</code> being created as a side effect of <code>:660</code>'s <code>mkdir -p</code> chain under <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS=agents</code> - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t32_parent_marker_written_only_on_create</code></li><li>[ ] AC 12 (traces_to: #1.12) - after uninstall NO <code>.cyberos-owned</code> file exists anywhere under the repo, including on an install-created <code>.agents</code> that is KEPT because the <code>:588</code> pointer's <code>.agents/rules/cyberos.md</code> survives; and an install-created <code>.agents/skills</code> whose marker the operator deleted still EXISTS and is reported as kept; the test MUST FAIL if a marker survives on a kept directory or if an adopted directory is removed - test: <code>tools/install/tests/test_install_hygiene.sh::t33_marker_removed_and_adoption_honoured</code></li></ul>\n<h2>3. Edge cases</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>RETRACTED: \"an operator hook with NO trailing newline cannot be restored byte-exact.\"</strong> The prior draft asserted this as an impossibility proof and it is FALSE. Install's <code>cat &gt;&gt;</code> appends exactly <code>\\n</code> + block (<code>:851-853</code>: the heredoc's first line is blank), so the byte immediately before the marker is ALWAYS ours, for every shape. Deleting <strong>that byte</strong> rather than <strong>that line</strong> inverts the append. Measured this round, install replayed verbatim then each strip: line-oriented 6B -&gt; 7B DIFFERS / byte-oriented 6B -&gt; 6B BYTE-EXACT; newline-terminated 7B -&gt; 7B both; three-newline 9B -&gt; 9B both; no-newline-with-content-above 24B -&gt; 25B line / 24B -&gt; 24B byte. The information is not destroyed at append time - it survives as the presence or absence of the blank line above the marker, and install's append is injective on hook content. The prior author's error was a level confusion: the rule was reasoned about in line-space, where the no-newline case has no blank line to consume, and \"my line rule cannot\" became \"no rule can\". §1.7 therefore binds on ALL pre-install hook content.</li><li><strong>The impossibility is real, but it is <code>.gitignore</code>'s and its cause is on the install side.</strong> <code>install.sh:733-746</code>'s awk does not append to <code>.gitignore</code>, it REWRITES it: <code>:744</code> buffers each line and <code>print</code>s it back with a terminator, and <code>:745</code> trims the trailing blank run. Measured with that awk applied ALONE (no block, no separator): <code>*.log\\n</code> (6B) -&gt; 6B unchanged; <code>*.log\\n\\n\\n</code> (8B) -&gt; 6B; <code>*.log</code> (5B) -&gt; 6B. Three distinct pre-install files collapse to one post-install state, so no uninstall-side rule can tell them apart - this is the pigeonhole the prior draft claimed for the hook, sitting on the other file. §1.7 is scoped to the newline-terminated, no-trailing-blank-run shape for <code>.gitignore</code> because that is the measured domain where install is injective. Closing the rest means changing <code>install.sh:744-745</code> to stop rewriting the file - a different and larger change than §1.11's two marker writes, and out of scope even though <code>install.sh</code> is now in scope for those. Recorded as an uncovered gap, not handed to a clause that cannot honour it. Re-measured this round and reproduced exactly.</li><li><strong>CORRECTED: the \"limit of the byte-oriented rule\" is a limit of the awk EMIT, not of the rule.</strong> The third author recorded that where an operator has added content BELOW our block with no trailing newline, \"an awk END clause re-adds one: want 17B, got 18B\" - and flagged it as their own rule's limit, which is the right instinct. <strong>The measurement reproduces; the attribution does not.</strong> Re-measured this round on the same shape with the same <code>sub()</code> and only the emit varied: <code>print $0</code> -&gt; <strong>18B DIFFERS</strong>; <code>printf \"%s\", $0</code> -&gt; <strong>17B EXACT</strong>. <code>print</code> appends <code>ORS</code>; <code>printf \"%s\"</code> appends nothing. So the shape IS recoverable, <code>printf \"%s\"</code> remains byte-exact on all four base shapes (6B/7B/9B/23B), and nothing here narrows §1.7. Kept as an edge case because the trap is real for anyone who reaches for <code>print</code>, and because it is the exact failure the round keeps repeating one level down: the author tested their own rule, which audit.md §3.2 records as the session's first instance of that discipline, and then stopped one step short of the cause.</li><li><strong>UNVERIFIED, and named rather than assumed: the byte-oriented strip is measured only on GNU awk.</strong> The expression above uses <code>RS=\"^$\"</code> whole-file slurp, which is a GNU extension, and it was measured on GNU Awk 5.1.0 on Linux. <code>install.sh:98</code> records that \"the payload's floor is POSIX\" and <code>:153</code> already branches GNU <code>-c</code> against BSD <code>-f</code>, so the payload runs on macOS's BSD awk, where <code>RS=\"^$\"</code> does not slurp. Whether the byte-oriented rule is expressible in BSD awk is NOT tested here. §1.7 binds on the BEHAVIOUR - delete exactly one byte, never a line - and not on any tool, so the clause stands and is implementable by other means; the implementer must not carry the gawk form over untested. Recorded because it is this author's own construct, and an originated claim is the one that arrives already believed.</li><li><code>CYBEROS_UNINSTALL_KEEP_BRAIN=0</code> vs the default: in the default path <code>.cyberos/</code> SURVIVES (<code>:151</code> removes it, <code>:155-158</code> recreates it with BRAIN inside); under <code>=0</code> it does not. §1.1's predicate is textual, so it is the same rule in both, and both are covered by AC 9. This is the premise the first draft inverted; the fix is not to pick the other mode but to stop conditioning on the mode at all.</li><li>A symlink into <code>.cyberos/</code> whose target was ALREADY absent before uninstall (a prior partial install): still provably ours by target text, still removed. Unresolvable is not unowned.</li><li><strong>The chained form is bounded by name, and that is not a name exemption.</strong> <code>.agents/skills/&lt;cmd&gt; -&gt; ../../.claude/skills/&lt;cmd&gt;</code> names no <code>.cyberos/</code> path, so it is ours by construction (install writes exactly that shape at <code>:662</code>, for exactly the three names at <code>:649</code>) rather than by target text. §1.1's \"no entry may be exempt by name\" is therefore about the DIRECT form only - it is what removes <code>:112</code>'s guard. Widening the chained rule to every entry under <code>.agents/skills/</code> would keep the pattern and lose the justification: an operator's <code>.agents/skills/my-notes -&gt; ../../.claude/skills/my-notes</code> matches it exactly. Bounding it to <code>:649</code>'s three names under <code>.agents/skills/</code> is precisely today's shipped behaviour at <code>:94</code>+<code>:98</code> - genuinely carried forward unchanged, and now stated as a scope limit rather than left as an accident of the loop.</li><li><code>CYBEROS_COPY_SKILLS=1</code>: the five native channels' copy fallback (<code>:613</code>'s <code>|| cp -R</code>) writes NO <code>.cyberos-owned</code> marker - only <code>.agents/skills/&lt;cmd&gt;</code> gets one (<code>:672-675</code>). So a copied <code>ship-tasks</code> under <code>.claude/skills/</code> is not provably ours and §1.3 keeps and reports it. It is untidy, not broken: a copy is self-contained and dangles at nothing. <strong>Its exclusion no longer rests on \"install.sh is out of scope\"</strong> - option C puts install.sh in scope, so that justification is retired and the honest one stated instead: this is an ENTRY-level ownership question under channel dirs the prune cannot reach (<code>grep -n 'rmdir'</code> returns only <code>:118</code>/<code>:119</code>/<code>:158</code>), so §1.6's container rule never fires on it and no deletion this spec authorises turns on it. Marking those copies would widen the task without changing any outcome §1.1-§1.12 decide. Named as an uncovered gap, not folded in for symmetry.</li><li><strong><code>.mcp.json</code> an operator hand-registered BEFORE install, byte-identical to ours.</strong> <code>install.sh:687</code> is create-if-absent, so install leaves it untouched; <code>:689</code>'s summary points operators at <code>.cyberos/mcp/README.md</code> to hand-register, so this is a supported path. §1.4 fires and removes the registration, mutating a path present before install. That is permitted by §1.9's carve-out and by nothing else: the registration's command names the machine we deleted, so the CONTENT is provably ours even though the FILE is not, and the file itself survives (§1.6). AC 9 pins the boundary - the file must still exist afterwards. An operator who wants the registration kept should keep the server.</li><li><code>.mcp.json</code> containing both our registration and an operator's: §1.5, not §1.4 - the file is not byte-identical to install's form, so it is left alone and the dead registration is reported. Surgically removing one key from arbitrary JSON needs a parser <code>uninstall.sh</code> does not have and <code>node</code> it must not require; reporting is what it can honestly do, and TASK-IMP-106's kept-list is the idiom for saying it.</li><li><strong>An operator's pre-existing EMPTY <code>.agents/skills</code> (or <code>.agents</code>) - the case the operator's decision turns on.</strong> <code>uninstall.sh:118-119</code> rmdirs both when they empty, with no ownership check: rmdir's failure on a non-empty dir is the only guard, and it does not fire when the dir is an operator's and happens to be empty. Measured end to end this round: with a pre-existing empty <code>.agents/skills</code>, install then uninstall DELETES it. That is a §1.9 casualty, not a tension - a path present before install goes missing. Under option C the marker decides it: no marker on that dir (install did not create it), so §1.6 keeps it and reports it. Where install DID create it, the marker is there, uninstall takes it back, and no empty dir is left behind - which is what option A would have cost.</li><li><strong><code>:119</code> is reachable, so gating it is not dead code.</strong> In the DEFAULT config <code>.agents</code> survives regardless of any marker, because the <code>:588</code> antigravity pointer writes <code>.agents/rules/cyberos.md</code> and NO uninstall code path removes it - so <code>.agents</code> is never empty and <code>:119</code>'s rmdir no-ops. (The survival is by absence of code: <code>grep -n 'rules/' uninstall.sh</code> returns only <code>:92</code>, a comment naming <code>.devin/rules/</code>, <code>.windsurf/rules/</code> and <code>.windsurfrules</code>, none of which is <code>.agents/rules/</code>. Citing <code>:92-93</code> here would be audit 1's ISS-006 - a three-path comment stretched to cover a fourth - so it is not cited.) That made <code>:119</code> look inert. It is not: measured with <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS=agents</code> (antigravity filtered off, no <code>.agents/rules/</code> written), <code>find .agents</code> after uninstall returns NOTHING - the operator's own pre-existing <code>.agents</code> AND <code>.agents/skills</code> are both destroyed. Both dirs therefore need their own marker and their own gate.</li><li><strong><code>mkdir -p</code> creates the whole chain, which is why <code>.agents</code> cannot inherit <code>.agents/skills</code>'s proof.</strong> Measured: <code>mkdir -p chain/agents/skills</code> creates <code>chain/agents</code> as well as <code>chain/agents/skills</code>. So when install runs <code>:660</code> in a repo with no <code>.agents</code> at all, ONE command creates both levels and a single marker in the child would leave <code>:119</code> exactly as blind as today. Compounding it, <code>.agents</code> has a SECOND creator - <code>:566</code>'s <code>mkdir -p \"$(dirname \"$abs\")\"</code> via the <code>:588</code> antigravity pointer, whose dirname is <code>.agents/rules</code> - and that one runs FIRST (566 &lt; 588 &lt; 660). Measured with <code>CYBEROS_AGENTS=antigravity</code>: <code>.agents</code> and <code>.agents/rules/cyberos.md</code> are created with no <code>.agents/skills</code>. §1.11 therefore tests each directory's own existence before any <code>mkdir</code> that could create it, rather than testing once at <code>:660</code>.</li><li><strong>The marker on a KEPT directory would be a new leftover, so it comes off either way.</strong> Where install created <code>.agents</code> and the antigravity pointer is installed, uninstall keeps <code>.agents</code> (its <code>rules/cyberos.md</code> survives by design) - and a marker left inside it would be a permanent file this task's own title forbids. §1.12 therefore removes the marker BEFORE the <code>rmdir</code> and regardless of whether the <code>rmdir</code> succeeds: the marker is provably ours, so §1.9 permits removing it, and the dir is simply kept without it. The sequencing is forced in the other direction too - the marker is a file, so while it is present the dir is never empty and the <code>rmdir</code> could never fire.</li><li><strong>Re-install after adoption keeps the adoption.</strong> If the operator deletes <code>.agents/skills/.cyberos-owned</code> to adopt the dir and later re-installs, <code>:660</code>'s <code>[ -d \"$d\" ]</code> test is TRUE, so install neither mkdirs nor re-marks, and the dir stays adopted across re-installs. That falls out of §1.11's create-test rather than needing its own rule, and it is the behaviour <code>:674-675</code>'s adoption sentence promises. The same test makes the marker write idempotent: a dir install created and marked is not re-marked on re-install.</li><li>An operator hook whose pre-install content already ended in multiple newlines: restore is byte-exact to THAT content - §1.7 consumes exactly one byte, never normalises. Measured byte-exact for a hook ending in three newlines (9B -&gt; 9B). Note this does NOT hold for <code>.gitignore</code>, where <code>:745</code> already trimmed those newlines at install time - see the second bullet.</li><li><code>CYBEROS_GLOBAL_SKILLS=1</code> copies <code>ship-tasks</code> into <code>$HOME/.claude/skills</code> and three siblings (<code>:634-637</code>); uninstall never touches them. Outside the repo is outside this task's contract (\"leave the repo as it found it\"); named so it is not mistaken for coverage.</li><li>Uninstall run twice: the second run finds nothing provably ours and removes nothing; §1.8's byte-identity still holds.</li><li>§1.9 compares post-uninstall bytes to PRE-INSTALL bytes, which is only meaningful for a file the operator did not edit between install and uninstall. An operator who edits their hook after install owns that edit and uninstall must not revert it; AC 9's fixtures do not edit between the two, and that is an assumption of the measurement, not a proven property of the code.</li><li>Security-class: ownership is decided by <code>readlink</code> output, our own marker file, our marker pair, and a command string naming our path - never by a path pattern an operator could forge by naming a directory <code>ship-tasks</code>. No user-supplied string is interpolated into a removal command; nothing printed is executed.</li></ul>";
